## Migration Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8**:

| API Found | Location | Pattern |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow + cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit gracefully; replaces ResetAbort + finally flow
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(2000)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO .NET 8 equivalent of Thread.Abort().
            // If GetNextItem/ProcessItem can't observe the token,
            // the thread will only stop when the process exits
            // (it's a background thread).
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `CancellationTokenSource` replaces `volatile bool` + `Thread.Abort`**
The bool couldn't interrupt a blocking `GetNextItem()`. A `CancellationToken` can — if you pass it through:

```csharp
// Before (blocks forever if GetNextItem is stuck):
_running = false;
_workerThread.Abort();

// After (unblocks cooperatively):
_cts.Cancel();  // wakes any token-aware blocking call
_workerThread.Join(2000);
```

**2. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token** — this is the critical part. If it blocks on I/O or a queue, pass the token:

```csharp
// Example: if backed by BlockingCollection<T>
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// Example: if backed by Thread.Sleep polling
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!TryDequeue(out var item))
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(500); // replaces Thread.Sleep(500)

    return item;
}
```

**3. `catch (OperationCanceledException)` replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`**
The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not someone else's.

**4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is simply removed** — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did, so `finally` blocks run normally without it.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing the token to blocking calls** | If `GetNextItem()` ignores the token, `Cancel()` won't wake it — the thread hangs until the process exits. Every blocking call in the chain must forward the token. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it silently** | Do cleanup, then `break` or rethrow. Don't loop back as if nothing happened. |
| **Expecting cancellation to be instant** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem()` takes 30 seconds with no token checks, cancellation waits 30 seconds. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long operations. |
| **Using `Thread.Interrupt()` as a replacement** | Also obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9). Use `CancellationToken` instead. |
